Suggestion for a new method: `_.findRandom(collection, [predicate=_.identity], [thisArg])`. Has the same signature as `_.find()`, but instead of finding always the first element that matches, it finds a random element that matches. A simple example implementation (not necessarily the best) would be:

``` javascript
_.findRandom = function(collection, predicate, thisArg) {
  return _.sample(_.filter(collection, predicate, thisArg));
};

var list = [ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 ];
var pred = function(x) { return x > 3; };
_.findRandom(list, pred); // 5
_.findRandom(list, pred); // 6
_.findRandom(list, pred); // 6
_.findRandom(list, pred); // 4
_.findRandom(list, pred); // 6
```

I think it would be a nice variant to `find` that doesn't always return the same element when multiple elements match the predicate. The method name could be different as well, just the first thing I thought of.
I can submit a PR later for this unless someone else wants to do it.

Currently lodash's `_.inRange` returns `false` for this statement: `0 < 2.9 < 3`, i.e. `_.inRange(0, 3, 2.9)`.
It'd make the function more useful when it can operate on non-Integer values.

An easy and mathematically sound fix would be to make it `left ≤ x ≤ right`, that is to make it a closed interval, which will hold true for arbitrarily (machine precision) close value like 2.99999999999; like so:

```
inRange: function(left, right, x) {
    return left - 1 < x && x < right + 1;
}
```

