I came across this trying to figure out why:

`_.times(3, _.times(3, _.constant(False)));`

returns `[0,1,2]`. The reason is that `_.times(3, _.constant(False))` doesn't return a function, so the outer `_.times` becomes equivalent to `_.times(3, identity)`. A more sensible default behaviour to me would seem to be to just error out (in my case I would like wrapping non-functions in _.constant, but I can imagine that would be confusing sometimes too).

